******
[1] Tibet Cases
Date: 8 Apr 2017
Source: Yahoo News [edited]
https://in.news.yahoo.com/1st-case-bird-flu-tibet-092412206.html


The 1st case of bird flu has been reported in Tibet, prompting Chinese authorities to halt live poultry trade in the remote Himalayan region, state media reported today [8 Apr 2017].

A 41-year-old migrant worker from neighbouring Sichuan province was diagnosed with the H7N9 infection on Monday [3 Apr 2017].

The man was quarantined at Tibet's Third People's Hospital in Lhasa, the regional health and family planning commission said.

He was involved in live poultry trade since arriving in Lhasa in February 2017, the state-run Xinhua news agency reported.

His symptoms were reported to the regional disease prevention and control centre on 2 Apr 2017, and his condition was confirmed on 3 Apr 2017.

He is the 1st human infection of H7N9 bird flu in Tibet. Following the diagnosis, live poultry trading has been suspended across the region. All those who had been in close contact with the patient have been put under medical observation, the report said.

H7N9 is a bird flu strain 1st reported to have infected humans in China in March 2013. Infections are most likely to strike in winter and spring seasons.

